de.boereck.matcher.helpers

Class ConsumerHelpers

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.boereck.matcher.helpers.ConsumerHelpers

  • public final class ConsumerHelpers
extends Object
    This class provides static methods that may help with defining consumers of cases in the found case library
    This class is not intended to be instantiated or sub-classed.

    • Method Detail

      • thenThrow

        public static <I> Consumer<I> thenThrow(Supplier<? extends RuntimeException> exSupplier)
                                 throws NullPointerException
        This method creates a consumer that ignores the input and always throws an exception provided by the given supplier exSupplier. Since the case found API works on Consumers, which do not declare checked excheptions, an the methods woking with consumers also do not declare checked exceptions, only RuntimeExceptions may be thrown. The supplier can be created from parameterless constructors of exception classes by reference to the constructor like this: ExceptionClass::new.
        Type Parameters:
        I - Type of object to be consumed.
        Parameters:
        exSupplier - supplier of exceptions to be thrown when the returned consumer is invoked. The supplier msut not be null and must not supply a null reference.
        Returns:
        Consumer that will ignore inputs and throws exceptions supplied by exSupplier instead.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - will be thrown if exSupplier is null.

      • thenThrowF

        public static <I,O> Function<I,O> thenThrowF(Supplier<? extends RuntimeException> exSupplier)
                                      throws NullPointerException
        This method creates a Function that ignores the input and always throws an exception provided by the given supplier exSupplier. Since the case found API works on Consumers, which do not declare checked exceptions, an the methods working with consumers also do not declare checked exceptions, only RuntimeExceptions may be thrown. The supplier can be created from parameterless constructors of exception classes by reference to the constructor like this: ExceptionClass::new.
        Type Parameters:
        I - type of input to returned function
        O - type of output to returned function. Be aware that the returned function will never actually return an object of this type, because it will always thrown an exception provided by exSupplier.
        Parameters:
        exSupplier - supplier of exceptions to be thrown when the returned consumer is invoked. The supplier msut not be null and must not supply a null reference.
        Returns:
        Function that will ignore inputs and throws exceptions supplied by exSupplier instead. The function will not return a regular return value.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - will be thrown if exSupplier is null.
